[Interested readers are recommended to access the original document where the dates are presented graphically in terms of the "Number of specimens positive for influenza by subtype." Overall there has been no significant change in the global pattern of seasonal influenza, other than the continued predominance of RSV (respiratory syncytial virus) in some parts of southern America. This may merely reflect differences in diagnostic capabilities and/or local interest. No novel genotypes of seasonal influenza viruses have made an appearance in any region of the world.

